# Accessibility Standards

**Role Perspective:** Senior Accessibility Engineer
**Standard:** WCAG 2.1 Level AA
**Scope:** iOS, Android, Web
**Philosophy:** Accessible by default, not as an afterthought

---

## Core Principle

> **Accessibility is a product requirement, not a nice-to-have.**
>
> Every feature must be usable by people with disabilities, including those using screen readers, keyboard navigation, and other assistive technologies.

---

## 1. Target Standard

**Required:** WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance

**Applies to:**
- ✅ Mobile apps (iOS VoiceOver, Android TalkBack)
- ✅ Web app (keyboard navigation, screen readers)
- ✅ All features, not just "public-facing" pages

**Why Level AA:**
- Industry standard for mobile and web apps
- Legally required in many jurisdictions (ADA, Section 508, AODA)
- Covers most common accessibility needs

**Not targeting Level AAA** (stricter, often not practical for all content)

---

## 2. Screen Reader Support

### 2.1 iOS VoiceOver

**Required for all interactive elements:**

```tsx
import { View, Text, Pressable } from 'react-native'

<Pressable
  accessible={true}
  accessibilityLabel="Submit RSVP"
  accessibilityHint="Submits your RSVP response"
  accessibilityRole="button"
>
  <Text>Submit</Text>
</Pressable>
```

**Rules:**
- `accessibilityLabel`: What the element is (noun)
- `accessibilityHint`: What it does (verb)
- `accessibilityRole`: Semantic role (button, link, header, etc.)

---

### 2.2 Android TalkBack

**Same API as iOS (React Native abstracts this):**

```tsx
<Pressable
  accessible={true}
  accessibilityLabel="Accept invitation"
  accessibilityRole="button"
>
  <Icon name="check" />
</Pressable>
```

**Why label is critical:**
- Icon-only buttons have no text for screen readers
- TalkBack would announce "Unlabeled button" without label

---

### 2.3 Web Screen Readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver macOS)

**React Native Web translates to semantic HTML:**

```tsx
// Becomes <button aria-label="Submit RSVP" aria-describedby="hint">
<Pressable
  accessibilityLabel="Submit RSVP"
  accessibilityHint="Submits your RSVP response"
  accessibilityRole="button"
/>
```

**Test with:**
- VoiceOver (macOS): Cmd + F5
- NVDA (Windows): Free, open-source
- JAWS (Windows): Industry standard

---

## 3. Accessibility Props (React Native)

### 3.1 Required Props for Interactive Elements

**All buttons, links, inputs MUST have:**

| Prop | Purpose | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| `accessible` | Mark as accessible element | `true` |
| `accessibilityLabel` | What it is | "Submit RSVP" |
| `accessibilityRole` | Semantic role | "button" |
| `accessibilityHint` | What it does (optional but recommended) | "Submits your response" |

---

### 3.2 Semantic Roles

**Use correct role for each element:**

```tsx
// Button
<Pressable accessibilityRole="button" />

// Link (navigation)
<Pressable accessibilityRole="link" />

// Heading
<Text accessibilityRole="header" />

// Image (decorative)
<Image accessibilityRole="image" accessibilityLabel="Event photo" />

// Image (decorative only, hide from screen reader)
<Image accessibilityRole="none" />
```

**Common roles:**
- `button` — Triggers an action
- `link` — Navigates to another screen
- `header` — Section heading
- `image` — Meaningful images
- `imagebutton` — Button that's an image
- `search` — Search input
- `none` — Decorative element (hidden from screen readers)

---

### 3.3 Grouping Related Elements

**Use `accessibilityRole="group"` for related content:**

```tsx
<View accessibilityRole="group" accessibilityLabel="Guest count">
  <Text>Adults: {adults}</Text>
  <Text>Kids: {kids}</Text>
</View>
```

**Why:** Screen reader announces "Guest count group: Adults 2, Kids 1" as one unit.

---

### 3.4 State Communication

**Announce dynamic state changes:**

```tsx
<Pressable
  accessibilityLabel={isLoading ? 'Submitting RSVP' : 'Submit RSVP'}
  accessibilityState={{ busy: isLoading, disabled: !canSubmit }}
  disabled={!canSubmit || isLoading}
>
  <Text>{isLoading ? 'Submitting...' : 'Submit'}</Text>
</Pressable>
```

**`accessibilityState` options:**
- `disabled: boolean`
- `selected: boolean`
- `busy: boolean` (loading)
- `checked: boolean | 'mixed'` (checkboxes)
- `expanded: boolean` (collapsible sections)

---

## 4. Touch Target Sizes

### 4.1 Minimum Size (Mobile)

**Required:** 44x44 points (iOS HIG), 48x48 dp (Android Material)

**Enforce with NativeWind:**

```tsx
<Pressable className="min-w-[44px] min-h-[44px] flex items-center justify-center">
  <Icon name="close" size={20} />
</Pressable>
```

**Why:** Fingers are less precise than mouse pointers. Small targets frustrate users.

---

### 4.2 Spacing Between Targets

**Minimum:** 8px between interactive elements

```tsx
<View className="gap-2">
  {/* gap-2 = 8px spacing */}
  <Button>Accept</Button>
  <Button>Decline</Button>
</View>
```

---

## 5. Color Contrast

### 5.1 Text Contrast

**Required ratios (WCAG AA):**

- **Normal text** (< 18pt): 4.5:1 minimum
- **Large text** (≥ 18pt or ≥ 14pt bold): 3:1 minimum
- **UI components** (buttons, inputs): 3:1 minimum

**Tools:**
- WebAIM Contrast Checker: https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/
- Figma plugins: "Contrast", "Stark"

**Example:**
```tsx
// ✅ Good: #333333 on #FFFFFF = 12.6:1
<Text className="text-gray-900 bg-white">High contrast</Text>

// ❌ Bad: #CCCCCC on #FFFFFF = 1.6:1 (fails AA)
<Text className="text-gray-300 bg-white">Low contrast</Text>
```

---

### 5.2 Non-Text Contrast

**Interactive elements (buttons, inputs, icons):**
- 3:1 minimum contrast with background

**Example:**
```tsx
// ✅ Good: Border visible against background
<View className="border-2 border-gray-700 bg-white" />

// ❌ Bad: Border too light
<View className="border border-gray-200 bg-white" />
```

---

### 5.3 Color-Blind Friendly Design

**Do NOT rely on color alone to convey information:**

```tsx
// ❌ Bad: Only color indicates success/error
<Text className="text-green-600">Success</Text>
<Text className="text-red-600">Error</Text>

// ✅ Good: Icon + color + text
<View className="flex-row items-center gap-2">
  <Icon name="check-circle" color="green" />
  <Text className="text-green-600">Success</Text>
</View>

<View className="flex-row items-center gap-2">
  <Icon name="alert-circle" color="red" />
  <Text className="text-red-600">Error</Text>
</View>
```

---

## 6. Keyboard Navigation (Web)

### 6.1 Focus Order

**Ensure logical tab order:**

- Top to bottom
- Left to right
- Follows visual layout

**React Native Web handles this automatically if using semantic roles.**

---

### 6.2 Focus Indicators

**All interactive elements must show focus state:**

```tsx
<Pressable
  className="p-4"
  style={({ focused }) => ({
    outline: focused ? '2px solid blue' : 'none',
    outlineOffset: 2,
  })}
>
  <Text>Button</Text>
</Pressable>
```

**Or with NativeWind (web focus styles):**

```tsx
<Pressable className="p-4 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500">
  <Text>Button</Text>
</Pressable>
```

---

### 6.3 Keyboard Shortcuts

**Common shortcuts should work:**

- `Enter` / `Space` — Activate button
- `Esc` — Close modal
- `Tab` — Navigate forward
- `Shift + Tab` — Navigate backward

**React Native Web handles Enter/Space automatically for buttons.**

**For custom shortcuts:**

```tsx
import { useEffect } from 'react'
import { Platform } from 'react-native'

if (Platform.OS === 'web') {
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleKeyDown = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
      if (e.key === 'Escape') {
        handleClose()
      }
    }

    document.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown)
    return () => document.removeEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown)
  }, [])
}
```

---

## 7. Form Accessibility

### 7.1 Input Labels

**All inputs MUST have labels:**

```tsx
<View>
  <Text accessibilityRole="header">Email Address</Text>
  <TextInput
    accessibilityLabel="Email address"
    accessibilityHint="Enter your email for the invitation"
    placeholder="name@example.com"
  />
</View>
```

---

### 7.2 Error Messaging

**Errors must be announced to screen readers:**

```tsx
<View>
  <TextInput
    value={email}
    accessibilityLabel="Email address"
    accessibilityErrorMessage={errors.email}
    accessibilityInvalid={!!errors.email}
  />
  {errors.email && (
    <Text
      accessibilityRole="alert"
      className="text-red-600"
    >
      {errors.email}
    </Text>
  )}
</View>
```

**Why `accessibilityRole="alert"`:**
- Screen readers announce immediately
- User knows validation failed

---

### 7.3 Required Fields

**Indicate required fields clearly:**

```tsx
<View>
  <Text>
    Email <Text className="text-red-600">*</Text>
  </Text>
  <TextInput
    accessibilityLabel="Email address, required"
    accessibilityRequired={true}
  />
</View>
```

---

## 8. Images & Icons

### 8.1 Meaningful Images

**Provide descriptive labels:**

```tsx
<Image
  source={{ uri: event.imageUrl }}
  accessibilityLabel={`Photo of ${event.name}`}
  accessibilityRole="image"
/>
```

---

### 8.2 Decorative Images

**Hide from screen readers:**

```tsx
<Image
  source={require('./assets/decoration.png')}
  accessibilityRole="none"
  accessible={false}
/>
```

---

### 8.3 Icon Buttons

**Always provide labels:**

```tsx
<Pressable
  accessibilityLabel="Close"
  accessibilityRole="button"
>
  <Icon name="close" />
</Pressable>
```

---

## 9. Modals & Overlays

### 9.1 Focus Management

**When modal opens:**
1. Move focus to modal
2. Trap focus within modal
3. Return focus to trigger element on close

```tsx
import { useEffect, useRef } from 'react'

export function Modal({ isOpen, onClose }: ModalProps) {
  const modalRef = useRef<View>(null)

  useEffect(() => {
    if (isOpen && Platform.OS === 'web') {
      // Focus modal on open
      modalRef.current?.focus()
    }
  }, [isOpen])

  return (
    <View
      ref={modalRef}
      accessibilityViewIsModal={true}  // Traps screen reader focus
      accessibilityLabel="Invitation details"
    >
      {/* Modal content */}
      <Pressable
        accessibilityLabel="Close modal"
        onPress={onClose}
      >
        <Icon name="close" />
      </Pressable>
    </View>
  )
}
```

---

### 9.2 Announcing Modal Content

**Use `accessibilityLiveRegion` for dynamic content:**

```tsx
<View accessibilityLiveRegion="polite">
  <Text>Your RSVP has been submitted!</Text>
</View>
```

**Live region types:**
- `polite` — Announce when screen reader is idle
- `assertive` — Interrupt and announce immediately

